Towards a Unified Resonance Framework: Connecting the Riemann Hypothesis and Yang–Mills Theory via Fractal Geometry

Abstract
We propose a unified mathematical framework in which the non‑trivial zeros of the Riemann zeta function and the mass spectrum of Yang–Mills theory arise as projections of a single underlying fractal resonance structure. This object, denoted 𝓕, exhibits both discrete and continuous spectral behavior. Its discrete projection yields the imaginary parts of the non‑trivial zeros of ζ(s), while its continuous projection yields the mass gap and higher excitations of Yang–Mills fields. We formalize the duality transformation 𝓓 that maps between these projections and derive a resonance equation linking both spectra. This approach suggests a deep structural connection between number theory and quantum field theory.

